In the last reel we sliced a stream into windows by event time, the moment something actually happened. But that leaves a hard problem hanging. Events don't arrive in the order they happened. A phone goes through a tunnel, a network hiccups, and an event that occurred at twelve oh three doesn't reach Spark until minutes later, late and out of order. So for a window covering twelve hundred to twelve oh five, how long do you keep it open, waiting for stragglers? Forever isn't an option, because an open window is state sitting in memory, and a stream that never ends would fill that memory until the job dies. Watermarking is how Spark draws that line, and I mean that literally, it's a line on the time axis.

Keep the same timeline in your head, and the same five-minute tumbling windows, W1 through W4. Now we add one moving marker, the watermark, and everything follows from where it sits.

Here's the definition, and it's worth memorizing. The watermark is the maximum event time Spark has seen so far, minus an allowed delay that you choose. On our timeline, the latest event Spark has seen is stamped twelve eighteen. You set the delay with withWatermark, passing the timestamp column and a threshold, here ten minutes. So the watermark sits at twelve eighteen minus ten, which is twelve oh eight. See that gap on the axis, the distance from the latest event back to the line, that gap is exactly your delay, the slack you've granted for lateness. And this line only ever moves forward, it trails the high-water mark of event time and never slides back.

That single line splits the whole axis in two. To the left, at or before twelve oh eight, time is closed. Any window that ends back there is finished. Look at W1, it covers twelve hundred to twelve oh five, and its end sits entirely behind the watermark. So Spark finalizes it, emits its result, and evicts its state, releasing that memory. That is the payoff, old windows behind the line are continuously cleared as the watermark sweeps forward, which is what keeps a never-ending stream running in a fixed amount of memory. To the right of the line, after twelve oh eight, windows are still open, still recent enough to keep accepting data.

Now watch a late event arrive and meet that line, because this is where it pays off. An event lands now carrying the event time twelve eleven. It's late, it arrived out of order, but twelve eleven is past the watermark of twelve oh eight, it's within the slack you allowed. So Spark accepts it and folds it into its proper window, W3. Late but not too late still counts, that's the entire point of the delay.

Then another event lands, this one stamped twelve oh three. That's behind the watermark. Its window, W1, was already finalized and evicted, so there's nowhere for it to go. Spark drops it. It's simply too late to matter. And that dropped event is the price of bounded memory. Choosing your delay is choosing where this line falls, more slack catches more stragglers but holds state longer, less slack frees memory faster but discards more late data.

There's one more thing the watermark unlocks, append output mode. Append can only write a row once it will never change again, and the watermark is precisely the signal that a window has closed for good. Without a watermark, Spark could never be sure a window was truly done, so append mode requires one.

So hold the whole picture as one image. A watermark is a forward-only line set at the latest event time minus your chosen delay. Windows that fall fully behind it are finalized, emitted, and evicted. Events with a time past it are accepted, even out of order. Events with a time behind it are dropped. That one moving line is what lets Spark wait just long enough for late data, then let go, keeping your streaming aggregations both correct and bounded. Pick the delay too tight and you lose stragglers, too loose and you carry state longer than you need, and that trade-off is yours to tune.
